{"/service/ndnp/rp/batch_rp_froghemoth_ver01/data/sn91070631/00516991677/1908061101/0493.xml":{"full_text":"/|ruiu) fcrihmt\nPROVIDENCE R. I.\nPLMLICATIOM OFFICSt\nIM-144 WK\u00bbTMI\u00bb\u00bbTBR STREET.\nFREDERIC N LUTHER\neditor.\nTHATCHER T. THURSTON.\nASSOCIATE EDITOR.\nPER MONTH. ?V. PWR TEAR.\nSINGLE COPIES ONE CENT.\nTELEPHONE\u2014UNION TSI\nPrivate Branch L'ichanae Cocnectlnr with\nAll Department!.\nEntered ae Beeord-CTe\u00ab Mail Matter Julr 4.\nJPO6 at the P<wt Office at Providence. R. 1.,\n\u2022nder the Act of OnrreM of March t. ISTS.\nUnsolicited manuscripts art submitted\nat the sender\u2019s risk of loss.\nThe Editor cannot make himself re\nsponsible for such matter, although he\nwill endeavor to return whatever is un\navailable for publication provided the\nnecessary postage is enclosed.\nReturn postage should accompany all\ncommunications to the Editor to which\na reply it desired.\nAnonymous communications will re\nceive no consideration what ver. t\nSubscribers going away for the sum\nmer may have The Tribune forwarded\nto them and the address cl iged as\noften as desired without extra charge..\nTHURSDAY, JUNE it, rooB\nTHE AVERAGE DAILY\nCIRCULATION OF\nChe mornins tribune\nFOR THE MONTH OF\nMAY\nWAS\n11,746\nEople*\nTwo Error*.\nIn his address before the brewers\nconvention in Milwaukee President Lieb\nmann made two statements that are\neven absurdly erroneous. He said that\nAmerican beer is \u2018'universally pure,'\u2019\nwhereas everybody who knows anything\nwhatever about this subject knows that\na great deal of the beer made in this\ncountry is unspeakably bad. He said,\ntdh, that \"very few of the men and\nwomen who preach prohibition have any\nfirst-hand knowledge of the saloons,\"\nwhereas the prohibition movement\nwhich is now causing the brewers so\nmuch alarm could never have succeeded\nas it has had it not been under the di\nrection of extremely practical and expe\nrienced persons.\nA Bnmper Harvest.\nThere is no reason to doubt the cor\nrectness of the prediction of Secretary\nWilson of the Department of Agricul\nture that there is to be a bumper har\nvest next fail. All the reports that\ncome\u2014from the grain-growing regions\nand the cotton belt alike\u2014are favorable;\nand in consequence Mr. Lane of the\nInter-State Commerce Commission\nfears that when the time comes for\nmoving the crops there will be no\nescape from a shortage of freight cars.\nFears on that score, however, will not\nset many persons grieving; they, too,\nmean the return of prosperity. Already,\nindeed, the railroads are turning to new\nconstruction again, and with that must\ncome, of course, increased activity in\nmany contributory industries. The thing\ngrows like compound interest.\nFnhmKtfn* to the Inevitable.\nIt is not surprising, surely, to learn\nthat the United States Steel Corpora\ntion has finally derided to reduce the\nprice of its product, inasmuch as it was\nrunning counter to laws of trade and at\ntempting to ignore conditions which\nactually exist and which soon or late\nmust be met. To continue the policy\nwhich was first adopted wntiJd have en\ntailed a heavy loss, of course, without\nimproving the situation or hastening the\nreturn of prosperity. The railroads\nhave also been experimenting along\nsimilar lines to a considerable extent,\nbut there is reason to believe that they,\ntoo, will be compelled to submit to the\ninevitable in the near future. There haj\nbeen a marked falling off in demand\nowing to reduced purchasing capacity\nand it is useless to endeavor to main*\ntain business on former levels.\nAn l nner*i*nry Appeal.\nPresident Roosevelt is as far re\nmoved, perhaps, from infallibility as any\nman in public life. Even in very im\nportant matters he frequently appears\nto act without thinking or, at least,\nwithout giving to the subject with\nwhich he is dealing the consideration\nwhich it deserves. Jn his utterances,\ntoo, he is apt to be indiscreet: he is im\npetuous and by no means so even-tem\npered as he might be. He has said\nsome things abnut the judiciary that\nwere better left unsaid Nevertheless\ngranting that his shortcomings are\nmany, it would be interesting tn learn\nif any Republican, or hemorrat fnr that\nmatter, really belies-es that President\nRoosevelt larks confidence in the integ\nrity and justice of the courts, national\nor State, nr that he would not agree\nthat the preservation of their mdepend-\nence and full constitutional preroga\ntives is essential to the maintenance of\nthe American system of government.\nUnless such a belief exists and unless\nit is supposed that Congress is power\nless to intervene there is no occasion,\nsurely, for petitioning *ihe Republican\nparty to save the courts from \u201can at\ntack designed to deprive them of their\npowers.\u201d\nMor* Antt-Aaloon Fffnrta.\nOn some accounts it would seem that\nhe active workers the saloon\nin this State might better confine their\nefforts for the immediate future to se\ncuring the proper enforcement of the\nnew license legislation rather than en\ngage in any movement for still more\nradical restraint of the liquor traffic.\nThe new law cannot be put into satis\nfactory operation without more or less\ndifficulty; and there will be plenty of\nopportunity for the earnest temperance\nworkers to uphold the hands of such\nofficials as may try to do their best and\nto bring to account such as may he dis\nposed to be remiss in duty. Besides,\nfairness and reasonableness might more\nnaturally suggest giving a fair trial to\nthis new law and noting its results be\nfore deciding what is best tn do next.\nOf course, however, the new law\nwhich the General Assembly has just\ngiven us, though a great improvement\nand, in fact, the best liquor law that\nthe State has ever had, is not final by\nany means; it is not going to satisfy the\nmore thorough friends of temperance\nindefinitely: there is a growing demand\nfor putting a much heavier hand on the\nliquor traffic than it imposes. It is not\nsurprising, therefore, to learn that an\nunusually vigorous movement is organ\nizing in Pawtucket and further up the\nBlackstone Valley for the establishment\nof a complete no license rule in those\nmunicipalities.\nWhile many would prefer a little ex\nperience under the law reducing the\nnumber of saloons before going any far\nther and while there must necessarily be\nsome doubt as to the wisdom of at\ntempting prohibition at this time in a\ncity \u00abo laige as Pawtucket, peculiarly\nconditioned as it is, nevertheless the\nmovement that is beginning cannot but\nhave some good effects. For one thing,\nit will keep the great subject of saloon\nreform before the local public in a con\nspicuous and striking way that will in\nfallibly help to educate popular senti\nment to demand the application of\nhigher standards in the future when\nconditions are riper. For another, it\nwill put the present licensed dealers on\ntheir best behavior.\nMuch has alreadv been accomplished\nby the no license agitation throughout\nthe country during the past few years\ntoward making ti e liquor dealers do\nsomething themselves, voluntarily, to\nminimize the evils of their business.\nI'he fear nf being forced tn close up al\ntogether because of popular opposition\nhas induced them tn look to their affairs\nas never before and to try to avert ini-\npending interference by making them\nselves and their business less offensive\nif not more reputable. At the big brew\ners\u2019 convention now in progress at Mil\nwaukee much of the discussion is of the\nelimination of some of the more objec\ntionable features of the liquor traffic\nwith a view to setting up a sort of\nback-fire against the prohibition which is\nrunning over many sections of the coun\ntry like flames in prairie grass.\nI ending the time\u2014if it ever can come\n\u2014when the saloon can safely be dis\npensed with altogether, there is some\npractical advantage in giving no-license\nagitations free course if for no other\npurpose than that the holders of licenses\nin an endeavor to prevent the open\nminded masses from becoming too in\ncensed with them, may be induced to\nconduct their business with more cir\ncumspection than they would otherwise\nthink necessary. Tn this way at least\nthe no-license movement that is starting\nin the Plackstone Valley may prove of\npositive public beneficence.\nConurrvln* National Rraonreea.\nThough it is less than a month since\nthe assembling of the Governors at\nWashington in conference with the\nPresident, consequences are already be\nginning to flow from it, the first evi\ndence being the action of the President\non a recommendation nf the conference\nin the matter of conserving the na\ntional resources. Not only with prompt\nness but with indications of having\ntaken extreme care in his selections he\nhas appointed a commission which is in\ntended to perform the double service of\nadvising the Federal Executive and co\noperating with whatever similar organ\nnations may be designated by the sev\neral States.\nSo far as it is permissible tn judge\nfrom the composition of the commis\nsion it sceems likely to be able to do\na deal of good of the most practical\nsort. The Chairman, Mr. Gifford Pin\nchot, has earned already more than a\nnational reputation for the energy and\nintelligence he has shown in the promo\ntion of the science of forestry. Sev\neral others of the forty-eight members\nof the commission are the heads of\nGovernment bureaus that are associated\nwith the natioh\u2019s forestry, geological nr\nreclamation service. Others have had\nexperience in Congress nr State office;\nthere are a few college professors\nwhose studies have taught them the\nneed of preventing the sacrifice of ma\nterials of industrial value: four are\nwell known engineers and there are also\nrepresentatives of labor, manufacturing\nand transportation.\nA more comprehensive nr better bal\nanced body it wntfd be difficult tn con\nceive; and much good may rightly be\nexpected of it. Rut nf course national\nauthority cannot accomplish everything\n7 he next step should be taken by the\nStates which are so situated as to have\na direct and deep interest in the im\nprovement of waterwavs. the prevention\nof flond*. the preservation of forests,\nthe reclamation of *wamp or arid lands\nor the more thorough utilization of min\neral deposits In all this work there\nwill be nerd of cooperation between\nthe Federal and the State Governments;\nTHE MORNING-TRIBUNE. PROVIDENCE. R. 1.. THURSDAY. JUNE 11. IW\u00bb.\nand before any programme can be ar\nranged there mint be thorough study\nand consultation. State commissions as\nwell as a national commission will lx\nneeded. The latter we now have; the\nformer should be provided soon.\nAndover** Removal Oppo\u00bb\u00bb4.\nThe turn which the new Andover con\ntroversy has taken was doubtless not\nunexpected in view of the fact that at\nthe recent Andover conference the pro\nposed affiliation of Andover Iheological\nSeminary and Harvard University met\nwith vigorous opposition. The Alumni\nAssociation of the seminary, which is\nthis werk celebrating its centennial, is\nnow determined to have the merger\nquestion, as it is called, submitted to\nthe Supreme Court of Massachusetts.\nWith that end in mind it was agreed\non Tuesday to lay the matter before the\nboard of visitors and urge upon it the\nadvisability of apf>ealing to that court.\nOstensibly it is the purpose of the re\nmonstrants to test the legality of the\naction that has been taken by the board\nof trustees, which is charged with run\nning affairs with Tt rather high hand.\nThat is, it is contended that the found\ners of the institution on Andover hill\nprovided dual governing boards, the ob\nject obviously bring to secure coopera\ntion in the administration of its affairs,\nand it is held that the board of visitors,\nwhose duty it has been to review the\nproceedings nf the trustees, has been ig\nnored by the latter in the decision\nwhich has been reached tn unite the\nseminary and the Harvard Divinity\nSchool Whether the board of visitors\nwas nnt consulted at all or w\u2019hether it\nwas overruled is nnt apparent, but in\nthe circumstances it seems somewhat\nsingular that it has uttered no protest\nand. as nearly as ran be ascertained, is\nnnt offended by the alleged discourteous\ntreatment which it is supposed tn have\nreceived from the body with which it is\nassociated At least, the course which\nthe alumni are pursuing leaves no other\ninference possible, inasmuch as their\nvote makes it clear that the board nf\nvisitors must be induced to stand be\ntween them and the trustees.\nIt is not improbable, however, that at\nthe bottom of the hostility which is\nmanifesting itself to the merger is a\nfeeling that Andover should not he per\nmitted to cast .its lot with Harvard;\nthat the two institutions have little in\ncommon from a religious point of view,\nand that if the seminary were estah\nlished in Cambridge it w\u2019ould speedily\nlose its identity, although it is not de\nnjed, nf course, that it is at the point\nof death at the present time and must\nbe transplanted or infused with fresh\nlife. As much was intimated, certainly,\nby a member of the Alumni Association\nwho. replying tn the objection that re\ncourse to the Supreme Court would\ncause delay, said that he suspected that\nthe seminary would not prosper at Cam\nbridge as he understood that none of its\nstudents intended to follow it to that\ncity. Still, that is a consideration en\ntirely apart, of course, from any ques\ntion upon which the Supreme Court\ncould be asked to pass.\nHowever politically radical the dom\ninating members of the Duma may he,\nthey are evidently not religiously\nheretical. The delegate has been\npromptly expelled who discussed dis\nrespectfully the ikons of the Orthodox\nGreek Church.\nIt might he inferred from President\nTaylor's discussion of present political\nconditions in his baccalaureate sermon\nat Vassar College that that institution is\nlargely attended by suffragettes.\nColonel Watterson does not see how\nanybody can be a Prohibitionist and a\nDemocrat at the same time; and many\npersons cannot see how anybody can be\neither at any time.\nIt might be inferred from his asser\ntion that he will not drop out of the\ncontest till the last gun is fired that\nSpeaker Cannon imagines he is now\nin it.\nThere is a lurking suspicion that if an\nemergency should arise the Honorable\nTimothy Wodruff could be persuaded to\naccept the nomination for Vice Presi\ndent.\nMr. Bryan insists that hr was paid no\nmoney to support Judge Parker. An\u00ab|\nso far as results were concerned it is\nplain enough that he didn\u2019t earn any.\nMost person*, no doubt, who know\nNewport at all will consider it even\nmore delightful because of the burning\ndown of its only summer hotel.\nThe arithmetic of the first ballot in\nboth of the bifr political conventions\nbegins to resemble an impossible prob\nlem in the higher mathematics.\nJudging from reports, cards of ad\nmission to the Chicago Convention are\nalmost as easy tn obtain as invitations\nto White House luncheons.\nThe contrast between what is printed\nabout Fourth of July noise and the noise\nitself that the press does not\nreflect public sentiment.\nTn a city of New York\u2019s resource*\novercrowded schonh are bad enough,\nsurely, hut underfed school children are\ninfinitely worse.\nThe Iz\u00bbui\u00abville Courier-Journal in\nti\u00abta that the chauffeur ahnuld he called\na driver. Another blow aimed at plu\ntocracy.\nSnrnrhnw th? drop in th? price of\n\u00abt??l doesn't \u00ab??m entirely compensatory\nfor the rise in th? price of meat.\nThe he*t rule hr hot weather con\ntinues tn be; Keep nut of the sun and\nAway frnm the thermometer.\naptain H*\"\u00bbh\u00ab.r\u00bbn ha< broken mjt agmn,\nbut, fortunately, war baan\u2019L\nBLOW TO BRYANISN.\nElection la Georgia a Proef That\nReaction Haa Met la.\n(From the Naw York Tlmae.)\nGeorgia, holding its Democratic Con\nvention on June 27, will be the Ust of\nthe State* to name delegates to Denver.\nIf the State Convention reflects the\ntemper of the people hr shown in the\nelection of Governor lest week, the dele\ngatee will go without instructions\u2014it\nwould certainly be surprising If they\nwere Instructed for Bryan. The lefeat\nof Hnke Smith appears to have been\nth* direct result of his ***l in making\nnumerous practical applications of the\ndoctrines of Mr. Bryan. Mr. Brown, the\nGovernor-elect, is not an orator, hut he\ncan write. He made his campaign with\nhis pen, presenting to the voters of\nGeorgia in a terse, pointed and effective\nway the consequences to them*gnd their\nbusiness and Incomes of the Bryan-\nHmith policy of harassing and mauling\nthe corporations.\nThe people of Georgia voted Smith out\nand Brown In. They served notice at\nth* polls that they had had enough of\nradicalism and agitation. They have ex\nperienced the effects of the destructive\nwork in which the Administration at\nWashington, Mr. Bryan and Gov. Hoke\nSmith are engaged, shd they say plain\nly that they don't like them. The elec\ntion of Mr. Brown was the most con\nvincing proof yet given that reaction\nhas set In and is gaining ground.\nIn Georgia \u00bbr In other Southern States\nthe policies nf Mr. Roosevelt and the\npreaching nf Mr Bryan have been popu\nlar. The rejection of both as embodied\nIn the candidacy of Hoke Smith la a\nmatter of sufficient moment to attract\nattention at Chicago as well as at Do.n\nyet. Two weeks work In Alabama gave\nGov. Johnson nearly forty per cent, of the\nDemocratic vote at the primaries. North\nCarolina, vfhere Gov. Glenn has carried\non the war against the corporations,\nfeels the impulse of reaction. There the\nconvention will b* held on June 21.\nUnder the unit rule the vote* of the\nConnecticut delegation will he cast\nagainst Bry-in. The Rhode Island dele\ngation. being equally divided, *an give\nhim but four votes. Tn Tennessee. Ken\ntucky, Virginia. Vermont, Colorado,\nUtah and Montana, w\u2019her* conventions\nare yet to be held, the result of the\nGeorgia election must have weight\nagainst the persuasions of Bryan\u2019s busy\nagents. The most rampant Bryanlte\nought to be sobered by the defeat of\nI Hoke Smith nn a platform of Bryanlsm.\nA Financial Pai\niFrnm th<\u00bb Tndfanannlla Nrwi.)\nA flaw has been found. It Is said, in\nth* Aldrlch-Vreeland emergency cur\nrency law In failing tn declare clearing\nhouse certificates to be illegal or tn for\nbid their issue. The expectation or tear\nIs that in case of another currency strin\ngency the banks, instead of expanding\nunde l the Aldrlch-Vreeland law. may\nsimply again Issue clearing house certi\nficates. of which they issued one hundred\nmillion dollars before. These cost noth\ning. while compliance with the law costs\nsomething It is added that the Treasury\nhopes to be able to exercise moral pres\nsure on the banks or to be the means\nof bringing the moral pressure of public\nopinion to bear and so to cause them to\nproceed under the law Instead of using\ntheir own old method of clearing house\ncertificates. We have a minimum of con\nfidence In the weight of moral pressure on\nfinancial institutions on questions of\nmoney, and particularly in time of panic\nor straitened monetary conditions. The\nsituation may ho described as a mess,\nwith expectations. If there should come\na strfngencj\u2019 at crop-moving time, busi\nness Interests suffering from money \"held\nup\u2019\u2019 by financial forces and then a resor'\nto clearing house certificates Instead of\nthe Aldrlch-Vreeland kind of currency,\nresentment will be roused and the accu\nsation will freely be made that the flaw\nnow discovered was provided for.\nWho Wants to hr o Remnant!\n(Fmm tho Atchlgon Gloh*,)\nA new social club will In* organised\nIn Atchison and will be called the \u201cRem\nnant Club.\u201d People too old to belong to\nyoung folks\u2019 clubs and ton young to be\ncontent to sit In an armchair nt home\nwill belong, as well as those too stupid\nto join Browning and Shakespeare so\ncieties\nTheir Only Chance.\n(From the Rochester Pemocrat and Chronicle.)\nA Chicago man wants a divorce be\ncause his wife scolds In her sleep. The\nlate hours kept hy some husbands, how\never, make it necessary for wives to\nacquire the art of scolding In their sleep\nIf they catch their husbands at home.\nMay hr He Was Poor.\n(Fmm the Houston Post\n\u2022\u2019You are not the first man to ask me\nto marry him!\u201d\n\"How did the other escape?\u201d\nIn a recent address a distinguished lay\nman declared that he believed that the\ndecline of interest In the cause of relig\nion should he attributed to a disposition\non the part of clergymen to make their\nsermons conform with the Ideas and re\nquirements of the wealthy members of\ntheir congregations. Juat what the Ideas\nand requirements of those members may\nbe they alone know, hut if they object\nto listening to preaching designed to\nrender them apprehensive and dissatis\nfied with themselves It la passing strange\nthat any nf them attend church.\nPossibly there ar* exceptions to the\nrule, but, for the most part, the pulpit\nhas borne down heavily on the rich man.\nHe has been informed almost every StiW\nday In the year that his possessions\namount to very little, even when they\nhave been honestly acquired, and that if\nthey have not been honestly acquired\nhe Is In reality poorer than th* poorest\nman. And he la frequently reminded that\nhe Is anything b\u2019H generous and that he\nought to be exceedingly doubtful con\ncerning hla future. Ministers of the gos\npel doubtless have their fallings, but for\nmany more years than one the rich man\nhas been a target for them; they have\nfired at -him until the leas fortunate in\nthe matter of this world\u2019s goods have\nturned and looked him over to see how\nhe was standing It. There was no mis\ntaking the m\u00abd< at which the preacher\nwas aiming. It may be that he apolo\ngised to the rich man after service and\nassured him that there might be some\nslight hope for him, hut he certainly om\nnot spsre him during the dlacnurse.\n\u2018n asaertloft that plutocrats are fa-\nEocal Society\nA society wedding and several out-of\ndoor fetes were pre-eminent In the \u2022octal\nlife of Providence yesterday. At 4'.#>\no\u2019clock In the afternoon Miss Anne T.\nPierce, daught arof Mr. and Mrs. J.\nI>*wia Pierce, wm quietly wedded to Prof.\nCharles Wilson Drown of Brown Uni\nversity. The ceremony was performed by\nRev. Edmund 8. Rouamaniere. rector of\nGrace Church, In the presence of the rela\ntive* and clone friends of the bride and\nbridegroom. A reception followed the\nceremony which was attended by mem\nbers of the faculty of Brown University\nand many prominent society people.\nThe wedding was unconventional In\nmany respects and picturesque In some of\nLts features. There were no bridesmaids\nand no beet ,man. Instead, the bride\nchose right of her old friends, who \u25a0toed\non either side of the bay window, where\nthe ceremony was performed, thus form\ning an aisle through which the bride\npassed on the arm of her father to meet\nthe bridegroom. These attendants were\nMrs. Theodore P. Bogert, Mrs. Howard\nI. Gardner, Mrs Rtephe-n C. Harris, Miss\nFMith Kimball, Miss Emma A. Taft, Miss\nHarriett W. Harris and Miss M. R. Rush\ner of New York.\nImmediately preceding the bride wan\nExllth Pogert, the little flower girl, In a\ndainty frock of white with blue ribbons\nand carrying a basket of marguerite* and\nforget-me-nots. The ushers were Prof.\nWilliam Kirk of Brown T\u2019nlversity. Mr.\nGenrge Parker Winship, Mr. Morris W.\nHouse of Providence and Prof. John\nDeur Irving of Yale College.\nThe bride wore a Prlncesse gown of\nwhite liberty matin ornamented with\nFlemlsh-lace and carried Hiles of the val\nley. Her attendants carried pink and\nwhite roses. Mrs. Pierce, mother of the\nbride, was gowned In black lace with\ngarniture of Duchesse lace.\n>t the close of the ceremony there was\nan afternoon tea served in a setting of\ngreen and while In the other rooms of\nthe residence were masses of stock and\npink and white peonies. The tea was\nserved by the eight attendants of the\nbride.\nAmong those Invited to the reception\nwere the following: President William\nHerbert Perry Faunce <of Brown, and\nMrs. Faunce. Prof. Benjamin Franklin\nClarke and Mn. Clarke. Prof. Winslow\nUpton and Mn\u00bb Upton. Prof. George\nGrafton Wilson and Mrs Wilson. Fred\nerick Taft Guild, Prof. Walter Cochrane\nBronson and Mrs. Bronson. Prof. Asa\nClinton Crowell and Mrs. Crowell, Dean\nAlexander Melklejbhn and Mrs. Melkle\njohn. Prof UndMy Todd Damon. Prof.\nGeorge Wyllys Benedict. Prof. Arthur\nHorace Blanchard and Mrs. Blnachard.\nDean Dida Rhaw King, Prof. Camlllo von\nKlenze and Mrs von Klenze, Mr. and\nMrs. Jeffrey Davis. Mr. and Mrs. Joseph\nGreen. Mr. and Mrs. Durfee, Wickford.\nMr. and Mrs. Harris D. Eaton, Calata.\nMe Mr. and Mrs. Trouts W. Dowrtes.\nMr. and Mra. Sidney Dean, St. Paul,\nMtnn.; Mr. and Mrs. John W. Daniel\nson, Mrs. Frederick Danforth. Buffalo,\nN. Y.; Amos Ijockwood DanJelsen\nPawtuxet; Mr. and Mrs. Charles Dexter,\nNew T*dford; Mr. and Mrs. William J.\nDyer. Miss Dyer. Miss Margaret Eager.\nMr. and Mrs Txmls T. Foster, the Mieses\nFoster, Mr. and Mrs M D Fernalu.\nCambridge; Mr. and Mrs. Albert R. Eus\ntis, Cambridge; Mr. and Mrs.* James Eus\ntis. Mrs. Charles Foster, Mr. and Mrs.\nAddison Q. Fisher, Mr. and Mrs. J. Her\nbert Foster, Miss Foster, Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge A. Freeman, Mr. and Mrs. H. P.\nDorchester, Miss Dorchester, Mr. and\nMra. Walter Day, Mr. William D. Fuller,\nMlm Julia Francis. Mr. Walter S. Fos\nter, Mr. and Mrs. Edward W. Foster,\nMiss Foster, the Misses Foster, Mr. and\nMrs. George L. Foster, Mr. and Mrs.\nHoward I. Gardner, East Greenwich;\nMiss Hope Nicholson, Mr. and Mrs\nHenry B. Nicholson, Mr. and Mrs. Rath\nbone Gardner, Mrs. John A. Nicholson,\nthe Rt. Rev. and Mrs. David H. Greer,\nMiss Greer, Mr. and Mrs. William Greer.\nMr. and Mrs. Dawrence Greer. Mr. ana\nMrs. Albert Gerald. New York; Rev. and\nMrs. Daniel Goodwin, East Grenewlch;\nMr. and Mrs. George A. Gouldtng. Mr.\nand Mrs. William S. Granger, Mies May\nGranger, Mr. and Mrs. Henry T. Grant,\nMiss Grant, Miss Sarah Greene. Mr. Ed\nward A born Greene. Mr. C. William\nGreene. Mr. and Mrs. Herbert Greene.\nMr. Frederick Guild, Brooklyn; Mr. and\nMrs F. A. Gaskill, Mrs. Thomas Harris,\nMiss Harris, Mr. and Mra. Stephen C.\nHarris, the Misses Harris. Mr. and Mrs.\nB. P. Harris. East Greenwich; Mr. W.\nB. Hosmer. Mrs. H. H. Hosmer, Mr.\nElsworth Huntington, Yale; Mrs. James\nHaslehurst, \u201cThe Buckingham;\u201d Mr. and\nMrs. Walter 8. Hackney, Mrs. Wil\nliam House, Miss House, Mr. and\nMrs. Ellkha H. Howard, Miss Howard,\nMiss Elizabeth G. King, Dr. and Mrs. E.\n1 B. Knight. Miss Amelia Knight, Mr. 8.\nvored by clergymen Is equivalent to an\nadmission on th* part of ths person mak\ning M that the la a stranger to houses of\nworship, and M may be feared that It Is\nthat sort of person who talks the most\nalboirt the decline of Interest In the cause\nof religion.\n\n\"An Item I read yesterday or the day\nbefore.\u201d Mid an observant cltiaen, \u201cmade\nme wonder how it happened that cats\never went tn the peins to get anything\naa violent as the rabies. The particular\ncat tn which my attention was called had\nhad the regies and had bitten several\npersons. I\u2019ve been studying cats all my\nlife, and at close range, too, and while\nI don\u2019t pretend to understand tnem 1\ndo know that there's considerable biutr\nabout them; they\u2019re make-believes, be\nsides being contradictory creatures.\n\u201cApparently cats are the most nervous\nanimals in the world; yet they\u2019re the\nbest sleepers. They'll dose curled im>\nfor hours and then stretch themselves\nand yawn and doge attain as If