 Shedd,\nEast Greenwich; Mra. Lfppitt Snow, Mrs.\nEdward P. Taft. the Misses Taft. Mr. and\nMrs. Orray Taft, Mr. and Mra. Franklin\nK. Taft, New York; Mr. Padelford Taft,\nSouth Carolina; Mr. Harry Taft, Mias\nEmma A. Taft, Mr. and Mrs. C. H. Tom\nkins. New Jersey; Mr. and Mra. A. K.\nTllllnghast. East Greenwich; Mr. and\nMrs. B. F. Vaughn, East Greenwich; Mr.\nand Mrs. Jameg Tower, Mrs. John\nTllllnghast. Gen and Mra. A. A. Wood\nhull, Princeton. N. J.; Mr. and Mrs. Leeds\nWaters. Col. and Mra. George H. Webb.\nMr. and Mrs. Clinton R. Weeden, Miss\nEva Weeden, Dr. and Mrs. H. A. Whit\nmarsh. Mrs. Mary E. Wadsworth. Mr.\nGeorge Waterman. Mra. Ella Williams,\nMiss Tjouls* Williams. Mr.\nGeorge F. Arnold, Brookline; Mr Craw\nford Allen. Prof, and Mrs. Francis G.\nA Denson, Misses Anthony, Prof, and Mrs.\nJohn H. Appleton, Mr. and Mra. Olney\nArnold. Miss Myrtle Burroughs. Mr. and\nMrs. Fred Burroughs. Prof, and Mra.\nJoseph Barrell. Mrs. A. C. Barstow. Mr.\nTheo. P. Rogert, Mr. and Mra. Frank\nHall Brown. Mias L. C. Beckwith. Mr.\nand Mrs. Thomas Rurrage, Portland; the\nMisses Bullock. Mias Irene B. Butter.\nMias Alice Bridge, Mra. Harrison P.\nBridger, Mrs. Gertrude Child Barrows.\nProf, and Mrs. William Beebe. Mrs. J.\nP. Campbell, Mr. and Mrs. Fred Carr.\nMrs. William Chambers, Miss Mildred\nChambers. Mr. and Mra. E. 8. Clarke,\nMr. and Mrs. William Corliss. Mr. and\nMrs. William 8. Crandall, Mr. and Mra\nPaul D. Chase. Brookline.\nAfter their return from a wedding\njourney Prof, and Mrs. Brown will live\nat 19 Di man place.\nODVRfT DINNER.\nMrs. William W. Douglas, wife of Chief\nJustice Douglas, entertained at a very\nbeautiful dinner at her home on Pros\npect street last night. The dinner was\ngiven In observance of the retirement of\nJudge Douglas from the Supreme bench.\nThe decorations were In buff and blue,\nsymbolising the State colors.\nA large mound of yellow and white\nmarguerites faced the cehtre of the. table\nand on either side of this were glass bas\nkets containing masses of bachelor but\ntons. The place cards were ornamented\nwith the State seal.\nThe dinner guests were Justice and\nMrs. Edward C. Dubois, Justice and Mrs.\nJohn T. Blodgett. Justice and Mrs. C. F.\nParkhurst and Justice and Mrs. Clarke\nH. Johnson.\nLAWN FETE\nRiver View was In holiday attire from\n8 to 10 o\u2019clock yesterday afternoon and\nevening, and the residence and grounds\nof Mrs Isaac Arnold were the scene of\na charming out-of-door fete for the bene\nfit of \"Neighborhood House.\u201d\nThe affair was given under the aus\npices of the Rhode Island Sorosls, of\nwhich Mrs. Frank H. Cady is President,\nand Neighborhood House Association.\nThe general committee was composed of\nthe following: Mrs Matthias W. Raker,\nChairman: Mrs. Frank H. Cady A Mi*\nJohn fl. WTiltehouse, Mrs. Charlee A.\nWlnsor. Mrs. L. W. Esten, Mrs. Foster\nTownsend, Mrs. W. I. Murdock. Mrs.\nHoward O. fltunges. Mrs. A. H. Field.\nMrs. E. B. fl. Brown. Mrs. Phillips. Miss\nElisabeth Mies Louise Dlman, Miss\nGordon.\nThe grounds were beautifully Illumi\nnated In the evening with Japanese lan\ntern\u00bb, while In the afternoon the great\nelms and flowering \u00bbhruba surrounding\nthe house made a charming Atting for\nan out-of-door feta. That the affair\nwould he an unqualified suoeeaa was, of\ncourse. a foregone condualon since Bo\nrosla was tn the lead and Mrs. M. W.\nBaker at the helm.\nIn the evening there was an entertain\nment In the River View Casino hard by\nthe house, and this was followed by\ndancing In charge of Mias Tz>ulse White\nhouse. Music for dancing was furnished\nby Mtea Whitehouse.\nThe entertainment consisted of a\n\u2018\u2022Punch and Judy\u201d show by Prof. Rose,\nfollowed by a little play entitled \u201cHix\nCups of Chocolate.\u201d The characters In\nthis were taken by the following girls of\nNeighborhood 'House; Mias Katherine\nMulvey. Mias Molly Dwyer, Mias Marga\nret Dooley. Mias Ella Hughes and Miee\nMaud Kenyon.\nA prominent part In the pldy was as\n\u2022umed by Miss Louise Keacn, daughter\nof Mr. Robert I* Reach of this city.\nMiss Keech also rave a brignt little mon\nologue entitled \u2022\u2019Unexpected Guests.\nThe tables on the lawn In the afternoon\nwere presided over by the following:\nCake\u2014Mrs. A. J. Bennett, Mrs. R. H.\nEddy, Mra. A. J. Arnold. Mrs. Ellery\nHall, Mrs. John C. Harrington. Mrs. Jo\nseph RrkkeT. Jr Mrs. Q J. Osler. Mra\nEdward Law. Mrs. J, F. Blauvelt, Mrs.\nPrimrose Williams; grabs Mrs. George\nThurber Brown. Mrs Annie H, Smith,\nMrs. Walter Smith. Mias Smith; lemon\nade.-JMra John B Smith, Mrs Dother D.\nBurlingame. Mrs. Pember. Mrs. Wattles.\nMrs. William Dunlap.\nThe cafe waa in charge of the general\ncommittee, assisted by Mrs. Isawr N.\nArnold. Mra J. C. Schott. Mrs. Salmon\nF Davis. Mrs. Herman Mor elock and\nMrs R T. Mingo. Mias Elisabeth lAdd\nhad charge of ths tables la the cafe and\nthe following young women were tti\u00ab\nwaitresses: Mri. Isabel Miller, Mis* Anita\nWatson, Ml*g Kthel Shipman, Mis* Cecile\ni\u00dfri<g\u00bb. Mis* BLeanor Bartlett, Mis*\nKatherine MacLeod. Mis* Frederika Mac-\nLeod and Mlm Hope\nIn a munmer house on th* lawn Miss\nGardner, the palmist, held her ghrlne, to\nwhich frequent pilgrimages were made\nby those to whom the unravelling of the\npast with possible rllmpe*, Into the fu\nture is an opportunity not to he missed.\nThis feature of the day was in charge of\n(Mrs. William Dyer and Mrs. Lunelle Al\ndrich.\ni Among those in attendance at the fete\nwere a little artist colony composed of\nMrs. Jean Paul Bolinger, the well-known\nartist of Boston; Mr. and Mra. Sidney\nR. Burleigh, Mr. W. Staples Drown and\nIMlss Angela O\u2019Leary, also Mrs. Freder\nick O. Fuller, Mrs. Arthur L. Claflin,\nMiss Tx>uisa Claflin, Misa Josephine \u00aeClr\n(by, Miss Marion Kirby, Miss Nellie\nYoung, Mra. John H. Whitehouse. Mrs,\n8. Newell Smith. Mrs. James M. Scott,\nIMra. Jack Finnigan, Dr. W. I. Sweet,\nMiss Maud Wilkinson. Mr. Maus Wheel*\nweight, Mr. M. W. Raker, Mr. Kenneth\nEarle, Mr. Ram Brown. Mr. Donald\nWhite. Mr. WtlMam Otis, Mrs. O. L.\nBearse. Mr. Jamea Otis. Mr. Howard\nWalker. Dr. George Crocker, Mr Everett\nHartwell, Miss Molly Rlii'kard, Mr. Ray\nOstby. Mra. Melville Otis. Mr Wharton\nWhitaker. Mra. Newton C. Arnold.\nSTRAWBERRY FESTIVAL.\nOn th* beautiful grounds of Mr. Alfred\nStone at Waterman street yesterday\nthere was an attractive lawn fete and\nstrawberry festival. The affair was given\nfor the benefit of Tu skat u eke t Cottage\nat Oakland Beach, the vacation home\nof the Rhode Island Working Women\u2019*\nClubs. There was a magician to fascinate\nthe children, a pony to ride and other\nfeatures, with music tn the evening.\nThe committee in charge of the affair\nwas Miss Kingsbury. Miss Jessie Rud-\nJpng. Miss FkHth Blanchard. Miss AUce\nKimball. Miss Mary Rpink. Miss Esther\nStone. Miss Mary Scott and Miss Nellie\nFairchild.\nThe various tables wore In charge of\nMrs. Ernest Church, Mrs. Clinton Gam\nwell. Miss Margaret Kimball, Mrs. Mac\nomber presided at the tea table and for\ntunes were told, with an Irish peacock, bj,\nMias Edith Blanchard.\nD. A. R- OTTING.\nGaapee Chapter, D. A. R roust be th\u00ae\nespecial friends of the elements, far\ncertainly all are not favored' with th\u00ae\nperfect weather for their annual outing\nwhich prevailed yesterday. The special\ncar which conveyed the daughters left\nCity Hall at 10:16, Ita destination being\nBarbour's Heights, a delightful spot not\nfar from the Pier, where the party wag\naugmented by ladles who came by auto\nmobile. Each one had provided nenseit\nwith sandwiches, olives, etc,, and th\u00ae\nhotel served cake, ice cream, tea, cof\nfee and chocolate.\nThe holiday spirit wan laid aside for a\nbrief space after lunch, quiet settled over\nthe merrymakers as Mrs. Amasa Eaton,\nVice Regent, caJled all to order to hear\nthe reading of the reports from the Con\ntinental Congress at Washington. The\nreport was read In two parts. Mrs.\nMitchell Dawes read Mis\u00ae Mary Greene's\nreport of the brilliant opening of the\nCongress and the decorations. She re\nported the unprecedented Increase of\nmembershlp.and alao the progress which,\nhas been made in the construction of\nContinental Hall. A pleasant little report\nof the giving of the silver loving cup to\nMr\u00ae. Barker was sent. She paid a special\ntribute to the President General, Mrs.\nDonald McLean, both as a woman, and\nas to her executive ability.\nMrs. William A. Potter presented tho\nsocial activities In a very painstaking,\ndetailed and humorous way. She told of\nthe many receptions accorded Mrs. Mc-\nLean, of the brilliant reception given by\nPresident Roosevelt and Mrs. Roosevelt,\nwhen Mrs. McLean stood at the Presi\ndent's right hand and introduced every\nDaughter by name.\n\u2019Mrs. Potter minutely described some o\u00a3\nth\u00ae gorgeous gowns worn by the Preai\ndent-General. It was said that one promi\nnent woman wore a different dress every\nsession, and another carried no less than\n30 harts with her.\nAfter the vote of thank* to the pro\ngramme committee for such a delightful\nday, adjournment was taken. When the\ntime for the car to leave waa announced\nthere w\u2019as a dropping of chins, and It was\nquestioned where the time had gone.\nSome one suggested that an advertise\nment In The 'lYUbune might And it, but\nthe sinking sun said \"No,\u201d so the car\nwas boarded ang home they came. Th*\nonly regret ot the day wag for the poor\nDaughters who didn't go.\nMrs. Jean Paul Selinger, the artist, of\nBoston, Is visiting her aged mother In\nSouth Scituate, she will visit her sis\nter, Mrs. George Thurston Brown, be\nfore returning to Boston. The Bellngere\nopen their studio at Crawford\u2019s, White\nMountains, July 6.\nTh* many frknd# of Mrs. Edwin A.\nBarrow* will be glad to know that she\niff recovering at her country home In\nBrlfftn) from a long and painful illneea\ncaused by a broken limb and' fractured\nankle.\nMr. and Mra. William Nivens are oc\ncupying the cottage of Mr. and Mra.\nBrown at Riverwide for a short time and\nhave as their guests Mra. Palmer, Miss\nBessie Palmer and Mr. Edward A. Brown.\nMlrb Caroline Grosvenor and Mias Rosa\nGrosvenor motored up from their vtll<\nat Newport yesterday and entertained\nfew friends at a luncheon at the A*a*\nwarn Hunt.\nMr\u00ae. Robert H. I. Goddard I\u00ae sailing\nfrom Europe for home In a few daya.\ntfbo will arrive home about the middle\not June.\nMrw Willkun Harkneaa Arnold will Mil\nfor Europe on June F. where she will\njoin her nuab&nd In lx>ndon.\nMiss Alice Dunbar of Washington. D.\nC, Is here as the guest of Miss Alice\nComstock.\nTHE TRIBtW lit MEW YORK.\nTh* Morning Tribun* is on sal* dally\nat j p. m. *t th* following hotels and\nnow* stand* In N\u00abw Jorl: Albert. A*tor\nHnus*. Belmont. Bartholdi, Breslin.\nBroadway Central, Cat* Martin. Cadillac.\nEvaratt. Fifth Avenue. Glls*y, Grand\nUnion. Herald Squat*, Hoffman, Holland.\nMarlborough. Murray HUI. Navarra,\nPark Avenue Flasa. Saranac, St Donia\nUnion -\u2019quara, Victoria. Wolcott, Waldorf\nAwtorla. York. Hotallng's n*w* stand* at\n40 Broadway. Fony-**cond street, Broad*\nway and Tnlrty-*lghth street and No 1\nPark Raw, and at Grand Central Statist*","height":"29127","width":"22464"}}
